category=Getting Started
description=<p>This example shows you how to gain or lose a scrollbar dynamically while the user is typing in a field, depending on whether the field contains too much text to fit.</p>
discussion=<p>The <font face="Courier" size="11">rawKeyDown</font> message is sent whenever a character key is pressed (and whenever a mouse scroll wheel is used). If the blinking text cursor is in a field, the <font face="Courier" size="11">rawKeyDown</font> message is sent to that field. When the <font face="Courier" size="11">rawKeyDown</font> message is sent to the field, it triggers this handler.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>In this example, the <font face="Courier" size="11">rawKeyDown</font> handler should be placed in the script of a field. The handler checks the contents of the field every time a key is pressed, and adds a scrollbar if the field's text becomes too large to fit. If the field already has a scrollbar and the user removes some text, the scrollbar is removed.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><font face="Lucida Grande" size="11"><b>Note:</b></font>  We use a <font face="Courier" size="11">rawKeyDown</font> handler instead of a <font face="Courier" size="11">keyDown</font> handler because <font face="Courier" size="11">rawKeyDown</font> recognizes even keystrokes that don't correspond to a character. For example, pressing the Delete key sends a <font face="Courier" size="11">rawKeyDown</font> message, but not a <font face="Courier" size="11">keyDown</font> message.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>The <font face="Courier" size="11">rawKeyDown</font> message passes a parameter, which is the keycode of the key that was pressed. In this example, however, we don't really care which key was pressed--we only need to know that the user typed a key, so we can check the height of the text--so we haven't used this parameter or assigned a name to it.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>This <font face="Courier" size="11">rawKeyDown</font> handler checks the <font face="Courier" size="11">formattedHeight</font> property of the field, which is the total height in pixels that the text would occupy if it were all displayed at once. If the <font face="Courier" size="11">formattedHeight</font> is larger than the field's height, the text is too large to fit completely within the visible area of the field. If the text won't fit, the handler shows a vertical scrollbar by setting the field's <font face="Courier" size="11">vScrollbar</font> property to true. If the text does fit, the handler sets the <font face="Courier" size="11">vScrollbar</font> to false.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Finally, the handler uses the <font face="Courier" size="11">pass</font> control structure to let the <font face="Courier" size="11">rawKeyDown</font> message proceed along the message path. If the <font face="Courier" size="11">rawKeyDown</font> message is trapped, the keystroke is not processed, so it's important to pass the message if you want the keystroke to appear. If you don't pass the <font face="Courier" size="11">rawKeyDown</font> message, you won't be able to type anything into the field.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><font color="#404040"><img src="202651"> Tip:</font> To save lines of code, we can rewrite the conditional in this handler like this:</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#0000FF">set</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> the </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#FF0000">vScrollbar</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> of </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#F88017">me</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> to \\</font></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">     (the </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#FF0000">formattedHeight</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> of </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#F88017">me</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> &gt; the </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#FF0000">height</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> of </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#F88017">me</font><font face="Courier" size="11">)</font></p>\n<p></p>\n<p>This does the same thing as the if control structure in the original handler: if the <font face="Courier" size="11">formattedHeight</font> is greater than the <font face="Courier" size="11">height</font>, the expression (<font face="Courier" size="11">the formattedHeight of me &gt; the height of me</font>) is true, so the <font face="Courier" size="11">vScrollbar</font> is set to <font face="Courier" size="11">true</font>. This is a little harder to read, but saves a line. You can use this same technique to transform any conditional that sets a property to <font face="Courier" size="11">true</font> or <font face="Courier" size="11">false</font>.</p>
level=2
licensed=false
name=Show or hide a scrollbar automatically as text is entered in a field
solution=<p><font color="#980517">on</font> rawKeyDown</p>\n<p>  <font color="#980517">if</font> the <font color="#FF0000">formattedHeight</font> of <font color="#F88017">me</font> &gt; the <font color="#FF0000">height</font> of <font color="#F88017">me</font> <font color="#980517">then</font></p>\n<p>    <font color="#68228B">-- there's too much text to fit, so show a scrollbar:</font></p>\n<p>    <font color="#0000FF">set</font> the <font color="#FF0000">vScrollbar</font> of <font color="#F88017">me</font> to true</p>\n<p>  <font color="#980517">else</font> <font color="#68228B">-- text will fit without scrolling</font></p>\n<p>    <font color="#68228B">-- get rid of the scrollbar</font></p>\n<p>    <font color="#0000FF">set</font> the <font color="#FF0000">vScrollbar</font> of <font color="#F88017">me</font> to false</p>\n<p>  <font color="#980517">end</font> <font color="#980517">if</font></p>\n<p>  <font color="#0000FF">pass</font> rawKeyDown <font color="#68228B">-- let the keystroke be processed normally</font></p>\n<p><font color="#980517">end</font> rawKeyDown </p>
title=Show or hide a scrollbar automatically as text is entered in a field